ionRef` |\\n| **Resumed session handling** | Unclear | No explicit handling or test for resumed sessions. Depends on whether Cursor's `transcript_path` always contains full history on resume |\\n| **Use agent's canonical export** | Pass | Reads from `transcript_path` provided by Cursor hooks |\\n| **No custom formats** | Pass | Stores raw bytes from Cursor's JSONL file directly in `NativeData` |\\n| **Graceful degradation** | Missing | No fallback behavior documented or implemented if transcript is unavailable |\\n\\n## Session Storage Abstraction\\n\\n| Requirement | Status | Notes |\\n|---|---|---|\\n| **`WriteSession` implementation** | Pass | Implemented, writes `NativeData` to `SessionRef` |\\n| **File-based agents** | Pass | Writes `NativeData` to `SessionRef` path via `os.WriteFile` |\\n| **Single format per agent** | Pass | Only stores JSONL native format |\\n\\n## Hook Events\\n\\n| Requirement | Status | Notes |\\n|---|---|---|\\n| **TurnStart** | Pass | `before-submit-prompt` -> `TurnStart` |\\n| **TurnEnd** | Pass | `stop` -> `TurnEnd` |\\n| **SessionStart** | Pass | `session-start` -> `SessionStart` |\\n| **SessionEnd** | Pass | `session-end` -> `SessionEnd` |\\n\\n## Rewind/Resume Support\\n\\n| Requirement | Status | Notes |\\n|---|---|---|\\n| **Rewind restores full state** | Unclear | `WriteSession` restores the transcript file, but no validation that Cursor actually resumes from it |\\n| **Resume command** | Questionable | Returns `\\\"cursor --resume \\\" + sessionID` - is this a valid Cursor CLI command? Cursor is a GUI app, not a CLI |\\n| **Session ID preservation** | Pass | Writes back to same `SessionRef` |\\n\\n## Testing\\n\\n| Requirement | Status | Notes |\\n|---|---|---|\\n| **New session (multi-turn, verify transcript)** | Missing | Only has hook install/uninstall + lifecycle parsing tests. No integration test for the full checkpoint flow |\\n| **Resumed session** | Missing | No test |\\n| **Rewind** | Missing | No test |\\n| **Agent shutdown** | Missing | No test |\\n\\n## Additional Issues Found\\n\\n1. **Dead code: `ParseHookInput` method** - `cursor.go:76` implements `ParseHookInput(hookType agent.HookType, ...)` which is **not part of the `Agent` interface**. The interface uses `ParseHookEvent(hookName string, ...)` (in `lifecycle.go`). The `ParseHookInput` method appears to be dead code from an older interface pattern that no other agent implements.\\n\\n2. **No `TranscriptAnalyzer` implementation** - Claude Code and OpenCode both implement `TranscriptAnalyzer` (for `GetTranscriptPosition`, `ExtractModifiedFilesFromOffset`, `ExtractPrompts`, `ExtractSummary`). Since Cursor uses the same JSONL format as Claude Code, it could likely reuse or share these implementations. Without `TranscriptAnalyzer`, Cursor gets degraded checkpoint quality (no transcript-derived file lists, prompts, or summaries in checkpoints).\\n\\n3. **No `TokenCalculator` implementation** - Other JSONL agents implement this for token usage tracking.\\n\\n4. **`FormatResumeCommand` is dubious** - `cursor.go:219` returns `\\\"cursor --resume \\\" + sessionID`. Cursor is a GUI IDE, not a CLI tool. This command likely doesn't work. Compare with Claude Code (`claude --continue --session-id=...`) or Gemini (`gemini ...`), which are actual CLI commands.\\n\\n5. **`transcript.Line` struct modified** - `transcript/types.go` adds a `Role` field to the shared `Line` struct. This is a cross-cutting change that affects all agents. Is `Role` actually needed? It's not used anywhere in the Cursor code in this PR.\\n\\n6. **`GetHookConfigPath` returns relative path** - `cursor.go:73` returns `\\\".cursor/\\\" + HooksFileName` (relative), while the hooks file is accessed with absolute paths in `InstallHooks`/`UninstallHooks`. This seems inconsistent - who calls `GetHookConfigPath` and what do they expect?\\n\\n7. **Assumption that Cursor's JSONL matches Claude Code's format** - The implementation reuses `transcript.ParseFromBytes` and Claude Code's `extractModifiedFiles` logic with Claude-specific tool names (`Write`, `Edit`, `NotebookEdit`). If Cursor's JSONL has a different schema, this silently produces wrong results.\\n\\n## Summary\\n\\nThe hook installation/uninstallation and lifecycle event parsing are solid and well-tested (23 tests). The main gaps relative to the PR 442 checklist are:\\n- No integration/E2E tests for the full checkpoint lifecycle\\n- No `TranscriptAnalyzer` implementation (degraded checkpoints)\\n- Dead `ParseHookInput` method should be removed\\n- The `FormatResumeCommand` needs to be verified against actual Cursor capabilities\\n- The `Role` field addition to the shared `Line` type needs justification\\n\",\"structuredPatch\":[{\"oldStart\":48,\"oldLines\":9,\"newStart\":48,\"newLines\":9,\"lines\":[\" \",\" 1. **Dead code: `ParseHookInput` method** - `cursor.go:76` implements `ParseHookInput(hookType agent.HookType, ...)` which is **not part of the `Agent` interface**. The interface uses `ParseHookEvent(hookName string, ...)` (in `lifecycle.go`). The `ParseHookInput` method appears to be dead code from an older interface pattern that no other agent implements.\",\" \",\"-2. **No `TranscriptAnalyzer` implementation** - Claude Code and OpenCode both implement `TranscriptAnalyzer` (for `GetTranscriptPosition`, `ExtractModifiedFilesFromOffset`, `ExtractPrompts`, `ExtractSummary`). Since Cursor uses the same JSONL format as Claude Code, it could likely reuse or share these implementations. Without `TranscriptAnalyzer`, Cursor gets degraded checkpoint quality (no transcript-derived file lists, prompts, or summaries in checkpoints).\",\"+2. **No `TranscriptAnalyzer` implementation** - Cursor's transcript format does not contain tool_use blocks, so file extraction from the transcript is not possible. This is expected - file detection relies on git status instead. (Not a bug, just a difference from Claude Code.)\",\" \",\"-3. **No `TokenCalculator` implementation** - Other JSONL age